<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-02-23T18:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-02-23T18:36:00-05:00" n="857" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d857">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/6324.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-02-23T17:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 23, 1913—5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>30. I think the effect would be excellent if, in case the atmosphere
                            clears measurably in the next two days, the Department would send to
                            this city the commanding officers of our boats in Vera Cruz with the
                            marines and such sailors as may be deemed advisable. I can make the
                            necessary arrangement here, if the Department approves my
                            recommendation.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>